Currently it doesn&#39;t exist a method to hide the underline in a `TextInputLayout`.  
However you can change the default color.  
To change the bottom line color with a FilledBox style you can use the **`app:boxStrokeColor`** attribute in the layout or the attribute **`boxStrokeColor`** in a style.

Something like:

    &lt;com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputLayout
        app:boxStrokeColor=&quot;@color/my_selector&quot;
        ...&gt;

or

    &lt;style name=&quot;ProfileDetail.TextInputLayout&quot; parent=&quot;Widget.MaterialComponents.TextInputLayout.FilledBox&quot;&gt;
        &lt;item name=&quot;boxStrokeColor&quot;&gt;@color/my_selector&lt;/item&gt;
        ....
    &lt;/style&gt;


This is the default selector used by boxStrokeColor:

    &lt;selector xmlns:android=&quot;http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android&quot;&gt;
      &lt;item android:color=&quot;?attr/colorPrimary&quot; android:state_focused=&quot;true&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;!-- 4% overlay over 42% colorOnSurface --&gt;
      &lt;item android:alpha=&quot;0.46&quot; android:color=&quot;?attr/colorOnSurface&quot; android:state_hovered=&quot;true&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;item android:alpha=&quot;0.38&quot; android:color=&quot;?attr/colorOnSurface&quot; android:state_enabled=&quot;false&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;item android:alpha=&quot;0.42&quot; android:color=&quot;?attr/colorOnSurface&quot;/&gt;
    &lt;/selector&gt;

It goes away if you set the background colour to transparent:

    yourEditText.setBackground(getResources().getDrawable(R.color.transparent));

where:

    &lt;color name=&quot;transparent&quot;&gt;#00000000&lt;/color&gt;

**EDIT:** After Gabriele&#39;s comment I checked again in my project and I can verify that the above solution works for me, as long as I change the background on the TextInputEditText view directly and not through the TextInputLayout. I think the idea is that the colour replaces the background drawable that includes the underline, and since the colour is transparent the view blends with the background.

**EDIT 2:** Also what seems to work for me if you want to edit the containing layout instead is: `mTextInputLayout.setBoxBackgroundMode(TextInputLayout.BOX_BACKGROUND_NONE);`

